The document provides a "WEEK-1 (SHORT & EASY VERSION)" which details a program to check grandparent relationships.

### Short Algorithm (5 Points)
1.  Store parent–child pairs in a list.
2.  Create a function to check if X is parent of Y.
3.  Create a function to check if X is grandparent of Y using the `parent()` rule.
4.  Call the grandparent function for given names.
5.  Print whether the grandparent relation is true or false.

### Simplified Program (Same Output)

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

struct Relation {
    char parent[20];
    char child[20];
};

struct Relation facts[] = {
    {"john", "mary"},
    {"mary", "susan"}
};

int isParent(char* p, char* c) {
    for (int i = 0; i < 2; i++)
        if (!strcmp(facts[i].parent, p) && !strcmp(facts[i].child, c))
            return 1;
    return 0;
}

int isGrandparent(char* p, char* gc) {
    for (int i = 0; i < 2; i++)
        if (!strcmp(facts[i].parent, p) && isParent(facts[i].child, gc))
            return 1;
    return 0;
}

int main() {
    if (isGrandparent("john", "susan"))
        printf("Yes, John is the grandparent of Susan.\n");
    else
        printf("No, John is not the grandparent of Susan.\n");
}
```

### Output
```
Yes, John is the grandparent of Susan.
```

